  Gauge theory solitons on noncommutative
  cylinder  


S.V. Demidov, S.L. Dubovsky, V.A. Rubakov, S.M. Sibiryakov

  
Moscow Institute of Physics and Technology,

Institutskii per., 9, Dolgoprudny, 141700 Moscow Region, Russia

   Institute for Nuclear Research of
         the Russian Academy of Sciences,
  60th October Anniversary
  Prospect, 7a, 117312 Moscow, Russia
   
We generalize to noncommutative cylinder the solution
generation technique, originally suggested for gauge theories on
noncommutative plane. For this purpose we construct partial isometry
operators and complete set of orthogonal projectors in the algebra
 of the cylinder, and an isomorphism between the free
module  and its direct sum 
with the Fock module on the cylinder. We construct  explicitly the
gauge theory soliton and evaluate the spectrum of perturbations about
this soliton. 
Introduction. 
Recently, field theories on noncommutative (NC) spaces have attracted
considerable interest (see,
e.g. Refs. 
for recent reviews and references to
ealier work). One of the motivations is the fact that
NC Yang-Mills theory emerges as effective low-energy
description of string theory in background
-field in a certain limit. Of particular 
interest is the study of solitons in NC theories. These solitons
share many common properties with D-branes;
most notably, correct values of D-brane tensions are 
reproduced, and the spectrum of fluctuations about
NC solitons is 
in qualitative and quantitative agreement with the
spectrum of open strings in D-brane backgrounds.

The best studied example of NC field theory is a theory on 
NC plane
(more generally, on noncommutative ). The algebra
 of
functions on NC plane is generated by two coordinates

and  obeying the following commutation relation,



This algebra is isomorphic to the algebra of operators in 
quantum mechanics of one degree of freedom.

In the limit of strong noncommutativity,  , solitons
of pure scalar theory are constructed in terms of projectors  in
the algebra  which satisfy



where  is multiplication in .
For gauge theory on NC plane, 
solution generation technique was suggested
 
which enables one to obtain new exact solutions starting from 
vacuum. This technique makes use of partial isometry
operators, which are elements  of the algebra  satisfying the
following properties,
SS^+=1,S^+S=1-P,
where   is a projector.
Thus, solitons in NC gauge theory obtained by the
solution generation technique are again labeled by projectors in
the algebra .

As explained in Ref. , the 
solution generation technique is closely related to an
isomorphism between the free module over the algebra 
  and the direct sum  of the
Fock module  
(which is merely the Hilbert space of harmonic
oscillator states) and the free module. In the case of NC plane, 
however, the use of the
formal algebraic language of projective modules may appear
an unnecessary sophistication, since the
 solution generation technique, as presented originally 
, is very transparent by itself.

The next simplest examples of NC spaces are NC
cylinder and torus.  Corresponding algebras will be denoted in what
follows by  and , respectively. In the case of
gauge theory on NC torus, it is problematic to construct a soliton in
terms of connection on  (to the best of our knowledge, no
explicit solitonic solution is known so far). 
One may still construct a NC gauge theory soliton as 
connection on ,
 the direct sum of the Fock and free modules
. 


 This approach
enables one also to calculate the
spectrum of small perturbations about the soliton
, 
which is in agreement with the spectrum of strings in 
 D0-D2 background, now in toroidally compactified 
space. However,  and  are not
isomorphic, thus a connection on 
 does not induce a connection on the free module
, and no solution generation technique emerges.

In this paper we find and study exact classical solutions of 
 gauge theory on NC cylinder (see Ref. for the
description of scalar solitons on NC cylinder 
in the large- limit). In particular, we discuss whether
an analog of the solution generation technique exists in this
case. We find an affirmative answer to this question and present
explicit solitonic solution directly in terms of connection on the
algebra . Unlike the case of NC plane, 
the algebraic formalism described in
Ref. proves  most adequate 
in gauge theory on NC cylinder. 

This paper is organized as follows.
In Section  we describe the algebra  of functions on
the noncommutative cylinder as a subalgebra of the algebra
 of NC plane. We introduce a basis in the Fock space
 which is convenient for constructing
projectors and partial isometry operators in 
the cylinder algebra . We also describe connections
on the Fock and free modules of this algebra.
In Section  we present the solution generation technique
for NC cylinder and give an explicit construction of gauge theory 
soliton as a connection 
on the free module . In Section  we study
the fluctuation spectrum about this soliton by making use of its representation
as a connection on the direct sum .

Non-commutative cylinder. 
Algebra, projectors, partial isometry operators 
In commutative  geometry, the algebra of functions on a cylinder
of radius  with coordinates 
may be defined as a subalgebra of functions on a plane, subject to
invariance under finite translations
A(x,p)= A(x+2R,p).
On NC plane with coordinates ,  generators of 
infinitesimal translations are inner 
derivations, 
A  x  =i  [p ,A ] ;
